WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.520
[Amit Varma]: What is a teacup? When I look at a teacup, I see a cup in which I drink tea. But others

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:13.600
[Amit Varma]: might see more in it. Looking at a teacup, they might see all the forces of history that

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:18.680
[Amit Varma]: shape it, the habits of society in a moment in time, all the different cultural influences

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:23.840
[Amit Varma]: around that give it the shape and weight and texture that we take for granted. A teacup

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.200
[Amit Varma]: contains so much information that it might even be talking to you. And all you have to

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:34.260
[Amit Varma]: do is listen. Now, at one level, I think this might be overthinking it, chai piyo aash karo.

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:39.440
[Amit Varma]: But at another level, it is true that all the inanimate things around us have rich histories

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:43.840
[Amit Varma]: and are full of meaning, if only we choose to look for them. I often say we should never

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:51.520
[Amit Varma]: take people for granted. Well, maybe we shouldn't take things for granted as well.

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:56.920
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:00:56.920 --> 00:01:04.240
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:04.240 --> 00:01:09.080
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen. My guest today is Annapurna Garimela, a designer, curator

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:13.640
[Amit Varma]: and art historian. She was one of my fellow judges for the JCB prize for literature earlier

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:19.880
[Amit Varma]: this year, just like the author Sarah Rai, who features in episode 255 of the show. Annapurna

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:24.520
[Amit Varma]: comes from a different imaginative world and sensibility than mine. And I loved our brief

00:01:24.520 --> 00:01:29.280
[Amit Varma]: conversation so much that I figured I had to get her on this show and have a longer

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:34.360
[Amit Varma]: chat. We finally made it happen. She shared her rich memories of growing up in a world

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:39.120
[Amit Varma]: that was partly rural and partly urban. I was struck by the richness and detail in her

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:44.120
[Amit Varma]: memories and felt that a world had opened up to me. We spoke about remembering and reflecting,

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:49.420
[Amit Varma]: academia and scholarship, art and access, the different ways in which we see the world.

00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:53.760
[Amit Varma]: We also argued a bit. She's wary of markets, while I love markets and technology because

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:58.440
[Amit Varma]: they've empowered and liberated individual creators like me and freed me from the whims

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:03.880
[Amit Varma]: of elite gatekeepers. Some of our conversation was transcendental, and some was combative.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:08.520
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure you'll find lots to think about. You'll also never look at teacups in quite

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:10.520
[Amit Varma]: the same way.

